[[File:Tennessee Residence.jpg|thumb|345x345px]] The '''Tennessee Governor's Mansion''', also known as the '''Tennessee Residence''', in [[Oak Hill, Tennessee|Oak Hill]], [[Nashville, Tennessee]], is the [[official residence]] of the [[Governor of Tennessee]] and his or her family. It is a three-story [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]]-style mansion that was built as a private home for [[William Ridley Wills]] and his family in 1929. It is on a {{convert|10|acre|adj=on}} tract about {{convert|5|mi}} south of the [[Tennessee State Capitol]] in Nashville. The state purchased the house in 1949 and it has served as the home of Tennessee's governors since then.<ref name=CommAppeal2009/>
The first renovation since the residence was purchased by the state was completed during the spring of 2010. The project was initiated in 2005 by [[Andrea Conte]], the wife of then-Governor [[Phil Bredesen]]. For years, maintenance had been deferred by governors wary of alienating voters. Prior to the renovation, the [[slate]] roof leaked, ceiling and wall plaster had many cracks, [[lead-based paint]] was peeling, and the residence was still heated and cooled by the original hot and cold water radiator system. Two other major problems were the relative lack of accessibility for disabled persons, and inadequate formal dining/gathering space. The formal dining room seated only 22 people, but state dinners often had more than 50 guests. In those situations, tents were erected on the front lawn along with port-o-let toilets for the guests of state to use. [[File:Conservatory Hall-CONTE SPEAKS.jpg|thumb|Conservatory Hall LEED certified extension built in 2009]] To address these problems, the [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]-based architectural firm [[Archimania]] was selected to design what was to be named [[Conservation Hall]], which was completed during the spring of 2010. It is a {{convert|14000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} mainly underground dining and meeting room capable of seating 160 people. The center of Conservation Hall is a glass-walled oval atrium that opens to the sky.<ref name=CommAppeal2009>{{cite news|newspaper=Commercial Appeal|location=Memphis, Tennessee |date=September 29, 2009 |title=Memphians planned governor's mansion change; Architects envisioned underground spaces |author= Richard Locker |url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/sep/29/memphians-plan-mansion-change/}}</ref> It is [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] (LEED)-certified,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2009/11/12/163035/Conservation-Hall-At-Governor-s-Mansion.aspx |title=Conservation Hall At Governor's Mansion Gets LEED Certification |newspaper=Chattanoogan.com |date=November 12, 2009}}</ref> the first governor's residence to be given the LEED designation.{{cn|date=May 2013}}
The house is open to the public for tours by advance reservation.
